01
The degree was always meant to be applied

A concentration in Marketing and Business Analytics from the O'Neill School wasn't studied in isolation — it was built to be used in environments where data and decisions are inseparable. Real estate turned out to be the perfect proving ground for that.

02
Data is a starting point, not a conclusion

Reporting without interpretation is just noise. The work I find most valuable translates channel data into real decisions — adjusting spend, shifting messaging, repositioning concessions. Measurement only matters if it leads somewhere.

03
Brand and performance are the same conversation

In real estate, a prospect's first impression is often a search result or a property website. Brand quality and conversion rate aren't competing priorities — they're the same goal, seen from different angles.

04
The best work happens in teams

Most of what I'm proud of happened alongside operations, revenue management, agency partners, and other marketing colleagues. Learning to contribute clearly in that environment — and to make the work around you better — is the actual job.
